`crates/ctx-cage/` is the process-sandboxing crate: it builds bwrap-based
cages, brokers tool execution and API egress across the sandbox boundary,
and ships the static mount assets and test suite that pin its ADR-encoded
security guarantees. A caller depends on this crate for `lifecycle::execute`,
`cli::resolve_mode`, and the bwrap/proxy/protocol types; internal argv
construction, frame encoding, and header rewriting stay private to `src/`.

The three subtrees are tightly bound by shared invariants rather than by
any code relationship: `assets/`'s `cage-resolv.conf` and `cage-nsswitch.conf`
implement the offline-DNS-fallback behavior that `src/bwrap/` mounts into
the cage and that `tests/bwrap_build.rs` + `tests/cage_assets.rs` jointly
verify (ADR-049) — a change to the DNS strategy touches all three
directories together. `src/`'s length-prefixed frame format is exercised
in `tests/protocol.rs`, `broker_loopback.rs`, and `proxy.rs` via real
transports rather than mocks, so a protocol change requires updating the
crate and revalidating all three test files. The real API key/credential
never crosses into the cage except through `src/proxy.rs`; nothing in
`assets/` or `tests/` bypasses that boundary.

`assets/` is passive configuration mounted by (external-to-this-crate)
setup code plus one prompt-injection doc; `src/` is the sandbox engine;
`tests/` is the executable spec for bwrap layout, DNS fallback, secret
masking, and stderr-safety during interactive PTY use.

No intent.md exists, so no divergence can be assessed.